# Brownfield Codebase Discovery

Analyze an existing codebase and produce a structured `knowledge/` directory.

> **Note:** Cursor does not support subagents. All document generation is handled directly
> in this session, one area at a time. The skill is organized around 5 discovery areas
> matching the AID discovery pipeline used in Claude Code. Checkpoint/resume logic
> skips existing files so the skill is safe to re-run after interruption.

## Inputs

- Codebase access (local path, git URL, or archive)
- For targeted discovery: GAP.md or IMPEDIMENT.md that triggered re-entry

## Discovery Areas

The 5 discovery areas and their output documents:

| Area | Owner (Claude Code) | Documents |
|------|---------------------|-----------|
| Architecture & Stack | discovery-architect | architecture.md, technology-stack.md |
| Modules & Conventions | discovery-analyst | module-map.md, coding-standards.md, data-model.md |
| Integrations & Domain | discovery-integrator | api-contracts.md, integration-map.md, domain-glossary.md |
| Quality & Debt | discovery-quality | test-landscape.md, security-model.md, tech-debt.md |
| Infrastructure & Gaps | discovery-scout | infrastructure.md, open-questions.md |

## Process

### Step 0: Check Existing KB

Scan `knowledge/` for existing files. Print: `[0/13] Checking existing KB...`

Expected documents:
```
architecture.md, technology-stack.md, module-map.md, coding-standards.md, data-model.md,
api-contracts.md, integration-map.md, domain-glossary.md, test-landscape.md,
security-model.md, tech-debt.md, infrastructure.md, open-questions.md
```

Skip any document that already exists. If all 13 exist, regenerate README.md and INDEX.md only.

---

### Area 1: Architecture & Stack

Print: `[1/5] Analyzing architecture and stack...`
Skip individual documents that already exist.

**architecture.md** — project type, folder structure, architectural patterns (MVVM, CQRS,
Clean Architecture, etc.), module boundaries, data flow, DI registration, entry points.

**technology-stack.md** — languages, frameworks, versions, package managers, runtime,
build system, dev tools (linters, formatters, type checkers).

---

### Area 2: Modules & Conventions

Print: `[2/5] Analyzing modules and conventions...`
Skip individual documents that already exist.

**module-map.md** — for each module: purpose, dependencies, size (lines/files), test
coverage estimate, key files.

**coding-standards.md** — conventions mined from actual code (not docs): naming patterns,
error handling, logging, config patterns, file organization. Mark inferred conventions
with ⚠️ Inferred from code — needs confirmation.

**data-model.md** — schema definitions, entity relationships, migrations, indexes,
validation rules.

---

### Area 3: Integrations & Domain

Print: `[3/5] Mapping integrations and domain language...`
Skip individual documents that already exist.

**api-contracts.md** — APIs exposed (endpoints, methods, auth, request/response shapes)
and consumed (external services, SDKs, HTTP clients).

**integration-map.md** — message queues, event buses, caches, webhooks, third-party
services, feature flags.

**domain-glossary.md** — terminology mined from class names, method names, constants,
and comments that encode business concepts.

---

### Area 4: Quality & Debt

Print: `[4/5] Assessing quality and tech debt...`
Skip individual documents that already exist.

**test-landscape.md** — test frameworks, test types (unit/integration/E2E), coverage
tooling, CI/CD integration, testing patterns, coverage gaps.

**security-model.md** — authentication, authorization, secrets management, input
validation, OWASP concerns. Note: static analysis only.

**tech-debt.md** — large files, circular dependencies, missing tests, TODO/FIXME density,
dead code. Classify each item: Critical / High / Medium / Low.

---

### Area 5: Infrastructure & Gaps

Print: `[5/5] Mapping infrastructure and identifying gaps...`
Skip individual documents that already exist.

**infrastructure.md** — CI/CD pipelines, Docker/container config, IaC (Terraform, Pulumi,
CDK, CloudFormation), environments, monitoring/alerting, deployment mechanism.

**open-questions.md** — everything that CANNOT be determined from code alone: uncertainties,
assumptions, gaps needing human input. Be comprehensive.

---

### Step 6: Generate README.md and INDEX.md

**knowledge/README.md** — completeness tracking table with ✅/⚠️ status per document
and revision history.

**knowledge/INDEX.md** — 2-3 line summary of every KB document:
```markdown
# Knowledge Base Index — {Project Name}

Use this index to find the right document before making assumptions.
If your task touches an area covered here, read the relevant document first.

| Document | Summary |
|----------|---------|
| architecture.md | {2-3 line summary of patterns found and structure} |
| ... | ... |
```

Regenerate INDEX.md on every discovery run (full or targeted).

---

### Step 7: Update Project Config Files

Scan the project root for `AGENTS.md` and `CLAUDE.md`. Replace any `<!-- AID:DISCOVER ... -->`
placeholders with real data from the analysis:

- **Project Overview** — project name, purpose, tech stack, target platform
- **Build & Test** — actual build, test, and lint commands
- **Code Conventions** — key naming patterns, formatting rules, idioms
- **Architecture** — high-level summary (layers, modules, entry points)
- **Project description** (CLAUDE.md) — project name and one-line description

Keep the `<!-- AID:DISCOVER ... -->` comment above each section.
Replace only `(pending discovery)` placeholders.
If a field cannot be determined: `(not found — check open-questions.md)`.

Print: `[13/13] Discovery complete — Knowledge Base ready`

---

## Targeted Discovery (Re-entry)

When a GAP.md or IMPEDIMENT.md triggers re-discovery of a specific area:

1. Read the GAP/IMPEDIMENT to understand exactly what's missing
2. Identify which area owns the missing documents (see table above)
3. Process ONLY that area — delete/overwrite only the relevant documents
4. Regenerate README.md and INDEX.md
5. Update `knowledge/README.md` revision history
6. Report completion to the calling phase

---

## Key Constraints

- **Write ONLY to `knowledge/` directory.** Never touch source code.
- **Every claim must cite a file path.** No unsourced assertions.
- **Mark inferred info** with ⚠️ Inferred from code — needs confirmation
- **Bash is READ-ONLY.** Permitted commands: `find`, `tree`, `wc`, `rg`, `cat`, `head`, `tail`

## Quality Checklist

- [ ] No overlap between KB documents
- [ ] Claims grounded in code evidence (file paths, line numbers)
- [ ] Inferred info marked with ⚠️
- [ ] open-questions.md captures everything needing human input
- [ ] README.md reflects completeness status and revision history
- [ ] INDEX.md generated with 2-3 line summaries of every KB document
- [ ] AGENTS.md and CLAUDE.md placeholders filled with discovered data
